  "prompt": "What is the difference between a hob and a stove? When would you use each?",
  "response": "Let me clarify the differences between a hob and a stove:\n\nHob:\n- A surface with cooking burners or heating elements\n- Usually built into a countertop\n- Typically gas, electric, or induction\n- Used only for cooking on top of the surface\n- Often part of a larger kitchen setup\n- More common in European kitchens\n- Generally smaller and more compact\n\nStove:\n- A complete cooking appliance with both a cooktop and an oven\n- Can be freestanding or built-in\n- Typically has burners on top and an oven below\n- Used for both stovetop and oven cooking\n- More common in North American kitchens\n- Larger and more comprehensive\n- Available in gas, electric, or dual-fuel models\n\nWhen to use each:\n- Hob: Ideal for smaller kitchens, apartments, or when you only need stovetop cooking\n- Stove: Best for full cooking needs, baking, roasting, and when you want a complete cooking appliance\n\nThe main difference is that a hob is just the cooking surface, while a stove is a complete cooking unit with both a cooktop and an oven.",
